# How to use sync-manager

Three packages:

| Package | Purpose |
|---------|---------|
| `@nu-art/sync-manager-shared` | Sync types, API definitions, deleted-doc DB def |
| `@nu-art/sync-manager-backend` | RTDB sync state, smart-sync HTTP API, automatic post-write timestamp updates |
| `@nu-art/sync-manager-frontend` | `ModuleFE_SyncManager` â€” RTDB listener, smart-sync client, per-module sync orchestration, `AwaitModules` component |

---

## What you must know

- RTDB timestamps are updated **automatically** via `PostWriteInterceptor` on every DB module. You do not need to call `onPostWrite` manually.
- Smart-sync compares per-collection `lastUpdated` timestamps between frontend (IDB) and backend (RTDB) to decide: no sync, delta sync, or full sync.
- Each `ModuleFE_BaseApi` participates in smart-sync when registered via a module pack in the Thunder builder â€” unless explicitly excluded.
- Entities with the same `frontend.group` in their DB definition share an IDB database and sync together.
- High-volume collections that should not be fully synced can be excluded via `ModuleFE_SyncManager.excludeFromSync(dbKey)` â€” see "Excluding a collection from sync" below.

---

## When adding sync-manager to an app backend

### Step 1 â€” Register the module

Add `ModuleBE_SyncManager` to the app backend module pack. No other wiring is needed â€” `init()` automatically discovers all `ModuleBE_BaseDB` instances and registers post-write interceptors.

```typescript
import {ModuleBE_SyncManager} from '@nu-art/sync-manager-backend';

// in app backend module pack
ModuleBE_SyncManager
```

### Step 2 â€” Understand what happens at init

During `init()`, the sync manager:

1. Discovers all `ModuleBE_BaseDB` instances via `RuntimeBE_ModulesDB()`.
2. For each DB module, registers a `PostWriteInterceptor` that computes `max(__updated)` from written/deleted items and patches the RTDB at `/state/ModuleBE_SyncManager/syncData/{dbKey}/lastUpdated`.
3. On first smart-sync request, `getOrCreateSyncData()` initializes any missing collections in RTDB â€” empty collections start with `lastUpdated: 0`, which updates on first write.

**You do not need to wire anything per collection.** Every `ModuleBE_BaseDB` is automatically covered.

---

## Frontend (`@nu-art/sync-manager-frontend`)

### How it works

`ModuleFE_SyncManager` listens to an RTDB node for per-collection `lastUpdated` timestamps. When a timestamp changes (backend wrote data), it debounces then sends a smart-sync request with every registered `ModuleFE_BaseApi`'s local `IDB.getLastSync()`. The backend responds with per-module instructions (no-sync, delta, full). The sync manager queues and executes them â€” full sync calls `query({where: {}})`, delta applies item updates/deletes â€” then sets `DataStatus.ContainsData` on each module.

### Starting and stopping

Sync is driven by login state. Start listening after login, stop on logout:

```typescript
ModuleFE_SyncManager.startListening();   // subscribes to RTDB
ModuleFE_SyncManager.stopListening();    // unsubscribes
ModuleFE_SyncManager.cancelSync();       // aborts in-flight syncs
```

### AwaitModules

Pages wrap content in `<AwaitModules modules={[...]}>` to wait until listed modules reach `DataStatus.ContainsData` before rendering. Only include modules whose data must be present before the page can render.

```tsx
<AwaitModules modules={[ModuleFE_MyEntity, ModuleFE_OtherEntity]}>
	<MyPage/>
</AwaitModules>
```

### Configuration

| Method | Purpose |
|--------|---------|
| `setNodeContext(resolver)` | Override the RTDB path (must match backend) |
| `setSmartSyncUrl(resolver)` | Override the smart-sync API URL |
| `setShouldCleanIDBOnFullSync(boolean)` | Whether to clear IDB before full sync (default `true`) |
| `setDebounceTimeout(ms)` | Debounce delay before sync fires |
| `setDebounceMaxTimeout(ms)` | Max debounce delay |
| `setOnSyncCompleted(callback)` | Hook after smart-sync response is processed |
| `setOnSyncDataChanged(callback)` | Hook when RTDB snapshot changes |
| `excludeFromSync(dbKey)` | Exclude a collection from smart-sync (see below) |

---

## Excluding a collection from sync

Some collections grow too large for full-collection sync (e.g. high-frequency time-series data). Use `excludeFromSync` to remove a collection from the smart-sync cycle while keeping its `ModuleFE_BaseApi` fully functional for on-demand queries.

```typescript
ModuleFE_SyncManager.excludeFromSync(dbKey);
```

**Where to call it:** In the FE module's `init()` â€” the module knows its own nature:

```typescript
export class ModuleFE_MyHighVolumeEntity_Class
	extends ModuleFE_BaseApi<DatabaseDef_MyEntity> {

	protected init() {
		super.init();
		ModuleFE_SyncManager.excludeFromSync(this.config.dbKey);
	}
}
```

**What changes:**
- The module is **not** included in the smart-sync request payload.
- The module's cache starts **empty** â€” it is not pre-populated on login.
- `query()`, `upsert()`, `delete()`, `cache`, `IDB` all work normally.
- The module's dispatcher still fires after queries, so `ComponentSync` listeners re-derive as usual.

**On-demand query pattern:** Components that need data from an excluded module query it scoped to what they display. Track the last-queried key to avoid redundant requests:

```typescript
class MyPage extends ComponentSync<Props, State>
	implements OnMyEntityUpdated {

	private lastQueriedId?: string;

	__onMyEntityUpdated() {
		this.reDeriveState();
	}

	protected deriveStateFromProps(): State {
		const item = resolveCurrentItem();

		if (item && this.lastQueriedId !== item._id) {
			this.lastQueriedId = item._id;
			ModuleFE_MyHighVolumeEntity.query({where: {parentId: item._id}});
		}

		const relatedData = ModuleFE_MyHighVolumeEntity.cache.allMutable()
			.filter(d => d.parentId === item?._id);

		return {item, relatedData};
	}
}
```

The flow: first render shows empty data â†’ scoped query fires â†’ cache populated â†’ dispatcher triggers `reDeriveState()` â†’ re-render with data.

**AwaitModules:** Remove excluded modules from `<AwaitModules>` lists â€” they will never reach `ContainsData` via sync, so including them would block the page indefinitely.

